--- !u!114 &3676149350792398938
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 5908324371096602647}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f4688fdb7df04437aeb418b961361dc5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Unity.TextMeshPro::TMPro.TextMeshProUGUI
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "This artifact is the Roped Pot (or Roped Vase) from Igbo-Ukwu, a masterpiece
    of 9th-century West African metallurgy. It is widely considered one of the most
    technically complex bronze castings ever created, predating the famous Ife and
    Benin bronzes by several centuries.\n\nThe Story of its Discovery\nThe history
    of this piece began with a chance encounter in 1938. A man named Isaiah Anozie
    was digging a water cistern (or a well) in his compound in the village of Igbo-Ukwu,
    Anambra State, Nigeria.\n\nThe Initial Find: As he dug, he struck several bronze
    objects. Not realizing their archaeological value, he reportedly gave some away
    to neighbors or left them lying around.\n\nFormal Excavation: News of the find
    eventually reached the colonial authorities and later the archaeologist Thurstan
    Shaw. In 1959, Shaw led formal excavations at three sites, which he named after
    the Anozie brothers on whose land they were found: Igbo Isaiah, Igbo Richard,
    and Igbo Jonah.\n\nThe Site: This specific pot was found at Igbo Isaiah, which
    appeared to be a storehouse or shrine filled with ritual regalia.\n\nHistorical
    Significance\nEarly Mastery: Carbon dating placed these artifacts in the 9th
    century AD. This shocked the international art world, as it proved that a highly
    sophisticated, wealthy society existed in southeastern Nigeria nearly a millennium
    ago, long before European contact.\n\nThe \"Rococo\" of Africa: Art historians
    have compared the intricate detail of Igbo-Ukwu bronzes to the work of Carl Faberg\xE9
    or European Rococo jewelry. The pot is cast using the lost-wax (cire perdue)
    technique.\n\nTechnical Marvel: What looks like a rope cage around the pot is
    actually part of the bronze casting itself. The artisans cast the vessel and
    the \"rope\" in separate stages and then joined them, showing a level of metallurgical
    skill that was unmatched in Europe at that same time.\n\nTrade & Wealth: Thousands
    of glass beads found alongside these bronzes suggest that the Igbo-Ukwu people
    were part of a vast trade network that likely reached as far as Egypt and the
    Nile Valley.\n\nSymbolism and Use\nThe vessel is believed to be a ritual water
    pot. In Igbo culture, such pots were often used for sacred cleansings or to hold
    water for a priest-king (the Eze Nri). The \"roped\" design is skeuomorphic\u2014it
    mimics the actual fiber nets used to carry or protect fragile clay pots, but
    here it is frozen eternally in bronze to signify the high status of the owner."
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
